Creating an entire ASP.NET web application is quite a detailed process, so I'll provide you with a basic structure and code snippets to get you started on building a Conference Room Booking System using HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and jQuery. This example will cover the front-end part of the application. Remember that you'll need to set up the back-end with proper APIs, data storage, and authentication to make a fully functional application.

**1. Create Project Structure:**

Create a new ASP.NET web application project in Visual Studio. Then, set up the project structure by adding folders for `css`, `js`, and `images`.

**2. HTML (index.html):**

Create an `index.html` file in your project and structure it like this:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Conference Room Booking System</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="css/style.css">
</head>
<body>
    <header>
        <h1>Conference Room Booking System</h1>
    </header>
    <main>
        <h2>Available Conference Rooms</h2>
        <ul id="roomList"></ul>
    </main>
    <script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-3.6.0.min.js"></script>
    <script src="js/script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

**3. CSS (style.css):**

Create a `style.css` file in the `css` folder to style your application:

```css
body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
}

header {
    background-color: #333;
    color: #fff;
    text-align: center;
    padding: 1rem;
}

main {
    max-width: 800px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 2rem;
}

ul {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
}

li {
    padding: 1rem 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc;
}
```

**4. JavaScript (script.js):**

Create a `script.js` file in the `js` folder to load conference room data using jQuery:

```javascript
$(document).ready(function () {
    // Simulated room data
    const rooms = [
        { name: 'Room A', capacity: 20 },
        { name: 'Room B', capacity: 15 },
        // Add more rooms here
    ];

    const roomList = $('#roomList');

    rooms.forEach(room => {
        const listItem = $('<li>').text(`Room: ${room.name}, Capacity: ${room.capacity}`);
        roomList.append(listItem);
    });
});
```

In this example, I've simulated the room data in JavaScript. In a real application, you would fetch data from a back-end API or a database.

Remember, this is a basic starting point, and you'll need to add features like booking forms, authentication, database integration, and more to create a complete Conference Room Booking System.

