**3. Sending Email Alerts:**

Sending email alerts requires integration with an email service. One common approach is to use SMTP to send emails from your server. In ASP.NET, you can use the `System.Net.Mail` namespace for this purpose. Here's a simplified example of how you might send an email:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Net;
using System.Net.Mail;

namespace ConferenceRoomBookingSystem
{
    public partial class ConferenceRooms : System.Web.UI.Page
    {
        // ... Existing code ...

        protected void SendEmailAlert(string bookingTitle, DateTime start)
        {
            try
            {
                string toAddress = "admin@example.com"; // Admin's email address
                string subject = "New Booking Approval";
                string body = $"A new booking has been made.\n\nTitle: {bookingTitle}\nStart: {start}";

                using (SmtpClient smtpClient = new SmtpClient("smtp.example.com"))
                {
                    smtpClient.Port = 587;
                    smtpClient.Credentials = new NetworkCredential("your_username", "your_password");
                    smtpClient.EnableSsl = true;

                    using (MailMessage mailMessage = new MailMessage("your_username@example.com", toAddress, subject, body))
                    {
                        smtpClient.Send(mailMessage);
                    }
                }
            }
            catch (Exception ex)
            {
                // Handle exception
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Remember to replace placeholders like `"admin@example.com"`, `"smtp.example.com"`, `"your_username"`, and `"your_password"` with your actual email and SMTP server information.

Please note that email handling involves security and configuration considerations, and it's recommended to use a well-tested email library and handle exceptions properly.

